Student Government: Join  
the crusade against Bigelow!

Rebecca M Jones

 

Students interested in helping to make
the dream of a traffic—free Bigelow
Boulevard a reality can now do so by join-
ing the Bigelow Boulevard Task Force.

The task force will be a group whose
main focus is to close Bigelow. It will con-
sist of three different divisions: research,
public relations, and a University coalition.

The research division will focus on
collecting information on the previous trial
closing of Bigelow, which will include
how local businesses and traffic were
affected. Researchers will also collect data
on how other urban schools have solved
similar problems in their areas.

The public relations division will be
using the research collected for publicity,
letter writing, and lobbying city council
members who may be opposed to the clos-
ing. .
The University coalition division of
the task force will be comprised of both
students and campus administrators. It will
be the students’ responsibility when work-
ing on this division to rally for student
support of the closing throughout the
University community.

Jennifer Molluso, the chair of the task
force, said this is an important issue, and
students should come to the first big meet-
ing on Thursday in order to show support
for the task force. It will be at 8 p.m. in the
SGB office in the William Pitt Union.

Molluso said there are a number of
reasons why students should support this
issue and join the task force. ‘

“Safety is an obvious important rea-
son,” Molluso said. “It’s not safe to play
chicken with these cars.”

Some people have proposed that the
University build a bridge connecting the
two sides of the street, rather than closing
Bigelow. Molluso said that would be
unsatisfactory.

“A bridge defeats the purpose. We
want a center for our campus, and Bigelow
runs right through what would be the cen-
ter of campus,” Molluso said. “People
don’t see a campus. They see buildings
scattered everywhere. We need an identity
for our University. We are lacking a col-
lege community atmosphere.”

If Bigelow closes permanently, ‘plans
such as creating a park-like atmosphere
seem to have the most potential. However,
to get students involved, Molluso has pro-
posed that the task force take ideas from
students on what they feel should be done
with the land.

One idea is to have students enter a
sort of contest by submitting their propos-
als to the task force, and one will be cho-
sen.

“Of course we can’t adhere to the
exact plans of a student because of engi-
neering purposes and potential costs of

plans, but the winning idea will be incor-
porated into the reconstruction of
Bigelow,” she said.

According to Molluso, both the
University of Pennsylvania and Ohio State
University have taken main streets on their
campuses and closed them off to traffic in
order to position a center point to their
campuses.

“Other universities have a central
location to their campuses. Why can’t
we?” Molluso asks.

One reason may be because during the
trial closing of Bigelow Blvd. last semes-
ter, many South Craig Street businesses
complained about the traffic during that
time. Cafe Azure, which is located on
South Craig, credited the closing of their
business to the onslaught of new traffic,

. according to Molluso.

“Bigelow was only closed for one
month. How could that have created a sit-
uation where they would have had to close
down?” she said.

Other businesses located closer to
campus have openly stated that they are
strongly in favor of keeping Bigelow open.
Some businesses, such as The “O,” have
even gone as far as to take out ads in local
papers to show that they do not support the
closing.

The “O” has said that during the test
closing, they lost about 30 percent of busi-
ness due to the traffic ﬂow and loss of
parking.

Molluso says that while official results
from the closing are still unavailable, she
has been given some ﬁgures early on.

According to these preliminary
results, about 76 percent of the traffic ﬂow
on University streets is not even from the
University employees or students, but
rather from people passing through to dif-
ferent areas of the city. Commuters ﬁnd it
easier to travel to locations such as
Squirrel Hill or Shadyside by using
Bigelow Blvd. in order to get onto Forbes
Avenue.

“During the closing, these commuters
found other ways to get where they were
going,” Molluso said. “It can be done.”

As the chair of the task force, Molluso
would like to see representatives from
each student organization (governance
groups, SGB committee members,
Greeks, etc.) at the meeting. Any other stu-
dent interested in this matter is encouraged
to attend also.

“We can make this happen, or we can
just do nothing. If we do nothing, nothing
will happen,” said Molluso.

The Bigelow Boulevard Task Force
meeting will take place Thursday night
at 8 p.m. in 617 of The William Pitt
Union. Applications are being taken for
the research and public relations divisions,
and for the University coalition. If interest-
ed, call Jennifer Molluso at the SGB
office, or stop by in 617 WPU.

 

