Just recently, I reread C.P. Snow’s
lecture on the two cultures debate. It
is an excellent work of literature
which is of interest to both humani-
ties and technical majors. The basis
of the lecture, which was given dur-
ing the early 1950s, is that there are
two separate intellectual cultures: the
scientists and the literary intellectu-
als. He argued that both of these cul-
tures were mostly concerned with
their own spheres of reality and had a
great deal of animosity for the other.
Some might say that while that was
the case nearly 50 years ago, great
progress has been made since then to
bridge the gap. Progress has been
made, but not nearly enough. If one
takes a look at the students of techni-
cal and humanities majors here at
Pitt, it is quite obvious that the prob-
lem has not gone away.

Being an engineering major for
the past few years, it has been my
privilege to listen to all the wonderful
gossip and inside jokes running
through Benedum Hall. In Benedum,
and to most engineers, the phrase
“CAS major” is almost a derogatory
term. Calling someone a “CAS
major” will always bring a deep
chuckle from those involved in engi-
neering. However, it is a two-way

THE PITT NEWS

street, and the insults go both ways.
When I tell humanities majors that
I’m an engineering major, they look
at me as if I’d just escaped from
Western Psych and say something
like, “You must be insane!” Or worse,
the word “geek” _can often be heard
muttered under someone’s breath.
But these are just the surface ani-
mosities, the important ones go much
deeper. Humanities majors are often
considered (by engineers) to be out of
touch with reality in the sense that the
entire world is pervaded with tech-
nology, and they all but ignore it.
Likewise, engineering majors are
considered to be
equally out of touch
with reality because
they are only con-
cerned with technolo-
gy where people are
often only an after-
thought.

Of course, these
are broad generaliza-
tions, and anyone actu-
ally believing all of
these things would be hard to find.
These attitudes are still here, howev-
er diluted they may be. It is a traves-
ty that nearly 50 years after C.P.
Snow’s lecture, not .much has
changed.

Like all insults, there is a grain of
truth to these. Engineers do some-
times get caught up in their own little
world, losing their human sides. As a
group, I think engineers are probably
the worst communicators. In the
