Dreams do come true. Ask Pitt red-
shirt freshman guard Kellii Taylor.

While in high school, Taylor was
recruited by more than a half dozen
schools. Syracuse, Georgetown,
Providence, and Maryland made it to
Taylor’s short list.

“What made me choose Pitt?  I
had a dream that I made it to the NBA,”
Taylor said. “First it showed me with a
Pitt uniform on. Then, I was in the
NBA. That’s what basically made me
come. I wanted to follow my dream.”

Taylor’s dream turned into a night-
mare in his first season when he suf-
fered a double—hemiated disk in his
back. The injury was severe, and after
surgery early in 1996, Taylor’s season
was over.

“It was hard. It was the worst year
of my life,” Taylor said. “I couldn’t
play. I was depressed. It was hard com-
ing over here and watching them play,
but I rooted them on and cheered them,
cause I wanted to win  I’d never had
surgery before in my life.”

Watching Taylor play this season,
one could never tell that he had been
injured at all. The six-foot, 175-pound
redshirt freshman is averaging 10
points, 2 assists, and 3.9 rebounds per
game. But his primary contribution has
been his defense.

